# Discus Fish: The King of the Aquarium

No freshwater fish commands the same reverence — and demands the same commitment — as the Discus (*Symphysodon* spp.). Their disc-shaped, laterally compressed bodies, extraordinary colour diversity, and complex social structure have made them the centrepiece of dedicated "Discus only" setups worldwide. They are not beginner fish. They require stable, very warm, soft, acidic water maintained with disciplined daily attention. But for experienced aquarists who meet their requirements, Discus reward that investment with longevity, personality, and visual impact unmatched in freshwater fishkeeping.

---

## Taxonomy and Species

The genus *Symphysodon* contains three recognised species:

**Symphysodon discus** (Heckel Discus) — The wild-caught "classic," recognised by three strong dark vertical bars, the most prominent being bar 5 (the middle bar). Found in the Rio Negro and blackwater tributaries. The most sensitive of the three to alkalinity.

**Symphysodon aequifasciatus** (Blue/Green/Brown Discus) — The primary source of most modern aquarium strains. Found in the central and eastern Amazon.

**Symphysodon tarzoo** (Red Discus) — Found in the western Amazon; thought to be ancestral to many "Red" colour strains.

Modern hobby Discus are almost entirely selectively bred hybrids developed from these species — producing colour forms that don't exist in nature: Pigeon Blood, Red Melon, Blue Diamond, Leopard Snakeskin, and hundreds more.

