## Temperature — The Non-Negotiable

Discus require temperatures most aquarists consider stressfully warm. **28–32°C is non-negotiable.** Below 27°C, Discus immune systems are compromised, they become prone to Discus Plague (a haemorrhagic skin condition) and hole-in-the-head disease, feeding drops off, and long-term health deteriorates.

The practical implication: Discus cannot be kept in community tanks with fish that prefer 24–26°C (which is most tropical fish). The short list of tankmates that genuinely tolerate 30°C+ includes:

- Cardinal Tetras (*Paracheirodon axelrodi*) — from the same blackwater Amazon habitat
- Rummy Nose Tetras (*Hemigrammus rhodostomus*) — prefer warm, soft water
- **[Corydoras sterbai](/species/corydoras)** — one of the few Corydoras comfortable at 30°C; others prefer cooler
- Altum Angelfish (similarly demanding; separate management required)
- Clown Loach (prefers warm; growth management required long-term)

