## Feeding

Discus are carnivores with unusually high protein requirements — a consequence of their warm environment (high metabolic rate) and their social feeding hierarchy.

### Staple Diet

**Beef heart mix** — The traditional Discus keeper's staple. Ground/blended beef heart combined with shrimp, garlic, spirulina, and vitamin supplements, frozen into cubes. High protein, high fat, and palatable to even reluctant feeders.

**Discus-specific pellets** — High-quality commercial pellets formulated for high protein delivery. Look for protein content above 45%.

**Frozen bloodworm** — Highly relished. Useful for conditioning and appetite stimulation in new fish.

### Live Foods for Conditioning and Breeding

Live foods are essential for conditioning breeding pairs and encouraging spawning:

**Baby Brine Shrimp (Artemia nauplii)** — Exceptional conditioning food, particularly for getting reluctant feeders onto food. Also critical for fry nutrition. **[Order live BBS from Blackwater Aquatics](https://blackwateraquatics.ca/collections/live-foods).**

**Live Blackworms** — Highly stimulating for Discus; burrow into substrate creating foraging opportunity. Excellent conditioning food pre-breeding.

**Daphnia** — Useful for conditioning; also aids digestion between high-protein feedings. **[Available at Blackwater Aquatics](https://blackwateraquatics.ca/collections/live-foods).**

**[Read about Discus conditioning and live food protocols on the Blackwater Aquatics Knowledge Base](https://blackwateraquatics.ca/blogs/knowledge-base).**

### Feeding Frequency

**3–5 small feedings per day** for optimal growth. Large, infrequent meals result in waste buildup and digestive stress. Remove all uneaten food within 10–15 minutes.

