## Social Structure and Behaviour

Discus form dominance hierarchies in groups. A tank of 5–8 will establish a pecking order where dominant fish get first access to food and premium territory. This is normal — ensure sufficient feeding stations and visual barriers to reduce constant chasing.

**Pairing:** As they mature (12–18 months), Discus begin pairing. Established pairs are highly bonded and display increased aggression toward other group members — a sign that breeding is imminent.

**Social signals:**
- Dark vertical bars intensifying = stress or aggression
- Horizontal body darkening = illness or severe stress
- Rapid side-to-side body shaking = breeding display between pair
- "Kissing" (lip-locking) = dominance contest or pair bonding depending on context

