## Disease

Discus are susceptible to a specific set of diseases most common in warm, heavily stocked, soft-water environments:

**Discus Plague (Freshwater White Spot Disease variant):** Dark colouration, clamped fins, resting on the bottom, loss of appetite. Often triggered by temperature drops or stress. Treatment involves raising temperature to 32–33°C and frequent water changes. Caused by Hexamita (internal flagellate parasite) in most cases.

**Hole-in-the-Head (HITH):** Pitting and erosion around the lateral line and head region. Caused by Hexamita infection exacerbated by poor water quality and high nitrate. Treat with Metronidazole.

**Gill Flukes:** Rapid gill movement, surface gasping, scratching. Common in imported fish. Treat with Praziquantel.

**Internal Worms:** Stringy white faeces, weight loss. Treat with Levamisole.

**Skin flukes:** Similar symptoms to gill flukes; lesions on body surface. Praziquantel effective.

Quarantine all new Discus for a minimum 4 weeks in a separate heated, filtered tank before introducing to an established group.

